Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

Cultural awareness is crucial in negotiations, though culture itself defies simple definition. Rather than being a uniform concept, culture is complex and multifaceted. It's misleading to make sweeping generalizations about national characteristics, such as claiming all people from a particular country share identical traits. Instead, negotiators should focus on understanding how cultural elements specifically impact their current negotiation and influence the dynamics at the table. People naturally interpret other cultures through the lens of their own experiences, making comparisons inevitable.

To effectively engage with different cultures, one should invest time in understanding their historical context and inherent biases. The key is not to judge or attempt to modify cultural practices, but to accept and work within their framework, particularly when negotiating from a position of lesser strength. When negotiating in unfamiliar territory, showing respect for local customs and beliefs helps overcome cultural barriers and facilitates progress.

Cultural differences extend beyond national boundaries into organizational contexts. Each company typically develops its distinct corporate culture, manifested in various aspects such as work schedules, dress codes, communication styles, and charitable practices. Even within the same country, corporate cultures can vary significantly between companies and even between different locations of the same organization. While some cultures may appear more homogeneous than others, such as the diverse American corporate landscape, deeper examination often reveals subtle but important variations.

Understanding cultural values is particularly crucial as they explain the motivations behind behaviors. For instance, in cultures that prioritize maintaining face or group harmony, negotiators will avoid actions that could embarrass their organization or superiors. Similarly, negotiators from cultures that value aggressive bargaining may be less inclined to accept quick settlements. While these cultural generalizations provide useful context, successful negotiators also recognize the importance of understanding their counterparts on an individual level.

The passage from Psalm 14, "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God,'" appears in both the Christian Bible and as an opening to St. Anselm's theological discourse. This sentiment aligns with Thomas Aquinas's perspective as well. In comparing their arguments for God's existence, we must accept their shared understanding of the Biblical God as our framework, rather than considering alternative divine concepts. This allows for a proper comparison of their specific theological defenses, though it's worth noting that neither provides a complete foundation for divine belief.

St. Anselm's approach centers on finding divine truth through internal reflection and faith. His argument suggests that since we can comprehend God in our understanding, we cannot truly conceive of His nonexistence. While his explanation can be complex, it essentially proposes that proof of God resides within human consciousness, requiring no external validation. This internal validation approach exemplifies the Christian concept of faith.

In contrast, St. Thomas Aquinas advocates for a more empirical approach, arguing that God's existence can be demonstrated through pure reason and observable evidence, independent of faith. This methodology would particularly serve evangelistic purposes, as it wouldn't require potential converts to accept unprovable concepts, instead relying on logical demonstration. Aquinas presents five logical proofs for God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. His approach resembles completing a puzzle - even with one piece missing, you can deduce its characteristics and existence through logical necessity based on the surrounding pieces.

In literary works, authors employ various techniques to evoke specific emotions or perspectives from their readers regarding crucial themes. In The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald masterfully demonstrates these methods, particularly through two distinctive approaches. First, he creates unique emotional resonance by combining seemingly mismatched adjectives and nouns. Second, and more significantly, he develops symbolic associations, especially through his strategic use of colors such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. Fitzgerald's most notable achievement is how he establishes specific meanings for white/gray and red/pink, then strategically deploys these colors to trigger particular emotional responses when readers encounter important elements in the story.

Fitzgerald establishes white and gray as symbols of conformity and uniformity, with white representing a more refined, upper-class uniformity, while gray suggests a more weathered, aged version. This symbolism is carefully constructed throughout the novel's early chapters. The text repeatedly presents characters in white attire - Daisy and Jordan are consistently described "in white," Nick appears in "white flannels" at Gatsby's gathering, Tom dons a "white shirt" for his meeting with Myrtle, and Catherine appears "powdered milky white." The only notable exception occurs during Nick's observations of Gatsby's party, where "primary colors" dominate the scene.

The author reinforces these color associations by applying them to mundane elements: New York's streets become "white chasms," party attendees' names fade to "gray names," and Catherine's living space is depicted as part of a "white cake of apartment-houses." The color symbolism extends to ordinary people and places: Jordan and Daisy's "white girlhood," the "gray cars" and landscape in the valley of ashes, and various background characters described as "gray." Once this color symbolism is established, Fitzgerald uses it to subtly characterize key elements, particularly Daisy. Her repeated association with white - from her clothing to her car - gradually transforms her from a distinct individual into a symbol of the uniform, conventional society that Gatsby desperately seeks to join.

San Diego County's favorable Mediterranean climate supports diverse agricultural production, featuring crops such as tomatoes, citrus, vegetables, fruits, honey, and peppers. The region has strong demand for organic, community-supported agriculture, with many programs having significant waitlists. Local organic farms often combine agricultural operations with recreational opportunities like hiking and birdwatching, allowing landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat and creating educational and revenue-generating opportunities.

Organic farming, while serving a profitable market niche, promotes greater biodiversity through chemical-free practices. However, it comes with challenges, including higher labor costs, more intensive management requirements for pest control and soil health, and potentially lower yields compared to conventional farming. Additional wildlife-friendly practices, such as cover cropping and strategic grazing, further increase operational costs, making financial assistance and expert guidance valuable for balancing profitability with habitat preservation.

The case study focuses on a 160-acre property near Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, bordering the Cleveland National Forest. The land, comprising chaparral, Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland, falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. This area supports numerous endangered and threatened species, including the Stephens' kangaroo rat and California gnatcatcher.

The property has a rich historical background, with Native American presence followed by late 1800s settlement by ranchers and wood sellers. Originally established through a homestead patent, the land likely served grazing and wood production purposes for many years. The study examined this real estate offering and available government programs to evaluate realistic options for small farmers interested in sustainable, wildlife-friendly operations, using a local organic farm as a model.

The relationship between brothers is characterized by an eternal, unbreakable connection that encompasses various emotions including affection, honor, envy, and brutality. Brothers share a unique understanding that allows them to see themselves reflected in each other, particularly during challenging times when their true nature emerges, whether positive or negative. This self-recognition through a brother's eyes reveals one's authentic self, not the persona others perceive, and their actions and their outcomes reveal their genuine character.

"The Scarlet Ibis" explores this brotherly dynamic through two siblings navigating their relationship amid richly detailed surroundings. Their journey, ultimately futile, culminates in a dramatic scene where fierce pride collides with crushing disappointment, resulting in one brother's death. The story conveys its message through the explicit portrayal of Doodle and his interactions with his brother, while the narrator's perspective illuminates the protagonist's complex emotional state and worldview, which significantly influence his behavior.

The protagonist's actions are fundamentally driven by pride and disappointment. He harbored dreams of a brother who could share in physical activities like breath-holding contests, running, climbing, and adventures at Horsehead Landing. However, Doodle's severe heart condition made such activities impossible, crushing these aspirations. The protagonist's frustration manifests darkly, even contemplating infanticide, yet this impulse dissolves when baby Doodle smiles at him. This transformation suggests an underlying, instinctive brotherly love beneath his initial resentment.

The human brain functions as an intricate system that processes information in sophisticated ways. Throughout history, people have tried to understand it through different comparisons - from ancient analogies like wax tablets to modern parallels with computers. However, it's important to remember that these comparisons have limitations and shouldn't be taken too literally.

The brain's information processing begins when sensory organs convert physical inputs (like light or sound) into electrochemical signals. These signals undergo two types of processing: bottom-up, which builds understanding from basic sensory details, and top-down, which uses existing knowledge to assist interpretation. For instance, when viewing a black box on white paper, bottom-up processing identifies basic features like edges and color, while top-down processing helps determine whether it's a solid object or a hole.

The brain employs an attention filter to determine which information deserves focus. This filter can ignore routine stimuli (like individual grass blades) while highlighting important information (like hearing your name in a crowded space). This filtering process occurs continuously throughout information processing.

Information storage in the brain occurs through multiple memory systems: sensory, working, and long-term memory. Information gets encoded differently depending on its type - for instance, words can be stored based on their appearance, sound, or meaning. Working memory temporarily holds information for about 20 seconds through neural electrical activity, while long-term memory appears to be preserved through protein structures.

Scientists have proposed various models to explain how knowledge is organized in the brain. One prominent theory is the semantic network model, which suggests that information is stored as interconnected concepts. For example, the concept of "chair" connects to related concepts like "table" and "wooden," creating a web of associated information.

The 2007 financial crisis in the United States devastated the economy, leading to widespread unemployment, a housing market collapse, and the downfall of major corporations. The crisis, which continues to impact the economy, stemmed from irresponsible political decisions that encouraged banks to issue risky sub-prime loans within an inadequate financial system. The situation worsened when Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were compelled to convert these mortgages into complex financial instruments (CDOs and CDS'). When borrowers began defaulting, banks' insufficient capital reserves triggered a chain reaction that affected the entire economy.

The crisis's origins can be traced to 1999 during President Clinton's administration. Seeking re-election, Clinton loosened lending restrictions, setting the stage for the future crisis. A New York Times journalist, Steven Holmes, presciently warned that Fannie Mae, under pressure from both the Clinton administration and shareholders, was expanding mortgage accessibility to lower-income borrowers, potentially requiring a government bailout during an economic downturn.

The crisis was further complicated by innovative mortgage products. The widespread use of adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs created deep interconnections between the housing market and other economic sectors. This led to excessive leverage in both households and financial markets, making them highly susceptible to price fluctuations.

When housing prices eventually collapsed, financial institutions holding mortgage-backed securities suffered severe losses. The five largest U.S. investment banks reported mortgage debts of $4.1 trillion in 2007, equivalent to 30% of GDP. This resulted in the cheap sale of Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch, Lehman Brothers' collapse, and forced Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley to become regulated commercial banks. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, carrying $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were ultimately placed under government conservatorship in September 2008.

Let's talk about exposition - that tempting opportunity in your writing where you might feel compelled to showcase your literary prowess. Unfortunately, it's often where you risk losing your readers to boredom or frustration. Even experienced writers like Dr. Merlin find themselves frustrated when encountering excessive information dumps in writing.

Here's the truth: exposition isn't your ally.

While most writers are familiar with the golden rule "Show, don't tell," many of us (Dr. Merlin included) still fall into the trap of writing lengthy passages where either nothing happens or too much is crammed in at once. It's like having two contradictory impulses: one pushing you to rush through background information to get to the exciting parts, and another urging you to detail every minute aspect of your characters' histories.

Exposition is essentially narrative explanation - telling rather than showing your audience what happened. In movies, it's when characters engage in unnaturally information-heavy dialogue. In written works, it's when authors directly explain rather than demonstrate.

Consider this scenario: Imagine reading a story where major life events - meeting a soulmate, having a grand wedding, and witnessing that spouse's tragic murder - are compressed into two pages with minimal dialogue. This approach deprives readers of experiencing the emotional depth of these moments. Instead, the story should allow readers to witness the husband's character through his actions and words, see how he enriches the heroine's life, and understand their connection. This investment makes readers genuinely care about his fate and better understand the heroine's subsequent journey.

The key is adding depth to basic plot points like "They met, they married, he died."

As writers, we must resist the urge to rush through character development by simply listing facts. For instance, when introducing a new character, it's tempting to rapidly outline their background: Air Force veteran, current night manager at a gas station, twice divorced, childless, weekend fisher, aspiring business owner, breakfast preferences and all. But that's not storytelling - that's just information dumping.

I analyzed two news broadcasts from NBC 4 in Columbus, Ohio on August 13, 2011. The primary story covered a domestic violence incident in Ashley, Ohio, where Shad Hostettler allegedly stabbed his wife multiple times. The brief two-minute coverage seemed appropriate given the developing nature of the story.

The broadcast then reported on Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old shooting victim in the Sharon Woods area, with SWAT Team involvement. The notably brief coverage of this incident appeared to reflect a concerning pattern of minimal media attention when victims are minorities, contrasting with the extensive coverage typically given to crimes involving white victims.

Following this was coverage of a Med-Flight helicopter incident involving a .22 caliber rifle shot, with Crime-Stoppers offering a $5,000 reward for information leading to an arrest. The weather segment briefly discussed predicted thunderstorms and temperatures in the mid-80s for the weekend, serving as a teaser for later broadcasts.

The news also covered a UDF robbery on Clime Road in Columbus, where I noticed disproportionate emphasis on the suspect's race and skin tone in the description. The final story discussed Texas Drug-Kingpin Rene Rodriguez's conviction for marijuana distribution to Ohio, curiously expressing his 25-year sentence as "300 months" and unnecessarily highlighting his ethnicity.

Exchange Traded Funds (ETFs) are investment vehicles that combine the tracking capabilities of index funds with the trading flexibility of stocks. They follow various assets, indexes, or commodities while offering advantages like short selling, margin buying, and single-share purchasing options. While ETFs charge lower fees compared to typical mutual funds, investors should note that trading them incurs commission fees similar to stocks.

The investment market offers a diverse range of ETF options, but prudent investors should carefully verify the marketed advantages, particularly regarding diversification claims. This analysis focuses on the IHF ETF, comparing it against its ten largest holdings to evaluate whether owning the ETF provides comparable benefits to holding a diverse portfolio of these individual stocks. The study also aims to determine if alternative combinations of these stocks might yield better performance metrics.

For practical purposes, the analysis concentrates on the top ten holdings, which represent 63.58% of the ETF's total assets. By normalizing these holdings to 100%, we can calculate how these stocks contribute to the portfolio's Beta and Return metrics, assuming a portfolio comprised solely of these ten stocks in proportions matching the ETF's allocation.

The findings reveal that a portfolio of just the top ten holdings outperforms the ETF by 6.11% (a 16% return increase) while maintaining a Beta that's 0.12 lower than the complete ETF. While these initial results suggest superior performance from the concentrated portfolio, further statistical analysis of the standard deviations is necessary to determine if the performance difference between these two approaches is statistically significant.

Analysis of Figure 17 reveals a significant decline in commuter log submissions during the project's third month. Several factors may explain this decrease. The winter season in New England naturally discourages bicycle and pedestrian commuting. The timing coincides with the fall semester's end, when the academic community is preoccupied with final assignments and grading. Additionally, the December holiday season and subsequent break result in reduced campus attendance. While the late January resumption of classes partially explains that month's low participation, the February decline remains puzzling. It's possible that the initial enthusiasm for such projects naturally wanes over time. We attempted to counter this trend with a targeted "Carpool Challenge Week" in March, which successfully boosted participation. A key lesson learned was the difficulty of maintaining momentum amid both natural engagement decline and academic calendar disruptions.

A fundamental obstacle to alternative commuting initiatives is the deep-rooted American cultural preference for personal vehicle use, which offers unmatched convenience and autonomy. To overcome this, incentivization proved crucial. While we distributed various local business gift certificates as rewards, we speculate that more substantial prizes (such as a bicycle or eco-friendly vehicle) might have generated greater participation. Furthermore, implementing an escalating prize structure throughout the project, rather than maintaining consistent reward levels, could have helped prevent the observed participation decline. For instance, announcing increasingly valuable prizes like bicycles in December and hybrid/electric vehicles in January might have sustained or even boosted engagement levels instead of seeing them drop.

While examining early Edison films in the Library of Congress collection, I analyzed fifteen trick films produced between 1895 and 1901. These productions utilized innovative editing techniques to create visual deceptions. My analysis primarily concentrated on identifying common artistic elements across most trick films while noting some unusual characteristics that emerged in later examples. The typical trick film of this era was characterized by several consistent features: studio-based settings, theater-style frontal viewing, stationary camera work, distant or medium-range shots, and single-shot compositions.

These films predominantly shared the characteristic of being filmed on indoor sets with a theater-like front-facing perspective. The camera remained fixed in its position, never tracking the movement of subjects. This approach, deeply influenced by theater and magic show presentations, resulted in horizontal movement patterns for the performers. For instance, in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors move laterally across the frame rather than toward or away from the camera.

The theater-inspired filming style typically employed long or medium shots exclusively, completely avoiding close-ups. This mirrored the theatrical experience where audiences viewed the entire stage performance from a fixed distance. The actors generally maintained their position in the middle ground, never approaching the camera closely enough to create what we would now consider a close-up shot.

Most of these early trick films adhered to a single-shot format, typically resulting in films lasting about a minute or less. This format limited their storytelling capacity, focusing instead on brief magical illusions, disappearing acts, and transformation tricks similar to vaudeville performances. However, it's worth noting that what appeared as a single shot to viewers often comprised multiple shots cleverly edited together to create magical effects. This can be observed in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), where careful observation reveals the editing point where the shot of the severed "head" is introduced, despite appearing seamless to casual viewers.

The Gothic Novel represents a paradoxical blend of old and new elements, as noted by Ian Watt. This literary form has experienced mixed reception, with some dismissing it as superficial while others celebrate its ability to evoke what Burke called the 'terrible sublime.' Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, considered the first Gothic novel, merged classical and contemporary romantic elements to establish a new literary genre. Walpole combined traditional theatrical devices with modern naturalistic narrative techniques in what he dubbed "A Gothic Story." The genre heavily draws from medieval theatrical elements, architectural styles, and customs. By Otranto's publication, the term "gothic" had acquired multiple meanings across various contexts and was often viewed as primitive compared to contemporary literary and social developments. The genre's enduring appeal stems from its unique fusion of theatrical Gothic elements with the novel's intimate psychological perspective, making it simultaneously timeless and revolutionary.

The concept of Chivalry stands as a central Gothic theme, particularly in The Castle of Otranto. Medieval chivalric ideals undergo both preservation and transformation in Walpole's work. Gothic authors, especially Walpole, emphasized chivalry to highlight the perceived decline of noble virtues in their contemporary society. Through chivalric references, the medieval past becomes idealized, foreshadowing Gothic literature's evolution into Romanticism. Walpole, writing during political turmoil, appeared to long for the moral certainties of an idealized Gothic era, contrasting them with his era's moral ambiguities. This perspective manifests clearly in characters like Frederic, who exemplifies traditional chivalric virtues through deliberately exaggerated characterization, establishing the Gothic tradition of excess.

Supply chain management encompasses the entire process of moving products from initial customer orders through raw materials procurement, manufacturing, and final distribution to consumers. This term was first introduced by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982 to describe the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling supply chain operations to meet customer needs efficiently. The framework consists of six crucial components: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information, which business managers utilize to deliver optimal customer service.

Production serves as the foundational first step in the supply chain process. During this phase, managers must determine the what, when, where, and how of product manufacturing. They analyze market trends to understand customer demands, which guides decisions about product types and quantities. Once these determinations are made, managers select appropriate manufacturing facilities based on volume capabilities and quality standards, while ensuring customer satisfaction remains paramount. The production phase also involves careful planning of work schedules and equipment maintenance. The importance of meticulous planning in this stage cannot be understated, as oversights can result in significant financial and time losses. For instance, major retailers like Walmart and Target implement detailed protocols for every business aspect, from employee dress codes to shipment receiving procedures, ensuring smooth operations.

Supply, the second key element, involves making strategic decisions about facility capabilities and partnership opportunities. Companies often operate multiple production divisions for single products, each with distinct equipment, workforce, and expertise. Managers must determine the most suitable division for various production processes or consider outsourcing to external partners. Outsourcing decisions are primarily driven by the pursuit of velocity – the ability to maintain quality and flexibility while optimizing cost efficiency.

The Victorian era's literary landscape was dominated by novels featuring meticulous detail and aristocratic themes. However, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights stand out as exceptions to this convention. These works incorporate mysterious elements and unusual narratives that deviate from typical Victorian literature, which serves to enhance character development and provide deeper insights into their psychological states and motivations.

The novels frequently employ dream sequences and hallucinatory states to achieve their mysterious atmosphere, though each work uses these devices differently. In Oliver Twist, these supernatural-like episodes often illuminate Oliver's inner psyche, revealing his struggles and his growing understanding of his circumstances. Chapter 28's depiction of Oliver's shooting experience, presented through a dreamlike state, exemplifies this technique. The scene emphasizes Oliver's powerlessness and deteriorating physical condition, demonstrated through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. His sensory confusion during the shooting, coupled with the "unseen hand" guiding him, highlights his complete lack of agency. The constant pain he experiences becomes intertwined with fear rather than shock, suggesting a deeper psychological impact.

This episode raises questions about fate and free will, as Oliver's passive response to life-threatening danger indicates his growing sense of helplessness. The passage suggests that Fagin's influence has begun to wear down Oliver's spirit, leading to a kind of learned helplessness that prevents him from fighting for his own survival. The description of time's distortion - the day passing without truly existing, and the night being simultaneously endless and fleeting - further emphasizes the psychological toll of these experiences.

While working as a tutor in an after-school program, I encountered a young Latino student named Adrian who struggled with reading. Despite speaking flawless English, he had unusual difficulties with certain letters. The mystery was solved when I met his Spanish-speaking mother - Adrian's reading challenges stemmed from unfamiliarity with the English alphabet rather than comprehension issues.

This experience highlights the complexities of language barriers in education, particularly in California. It demonstrates how language challenges aren't always obvious, even when students speak English fluently. While Adrian's situation required focused tutoring in English alphabet and pronunciation, many students with limited English proficiency need more comprehensive solutions.

No single approach - whether dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, or ESL classes - can completely address this issue. The solution lies in implementing multiple strategies simultaneously. The dual language system, in particular, shows promise for all students, not just Spanish speakers. Research indicates that children in two-way bilingual programs often perform better academically than their peers. While requiring all teachers to be bilingual might be impractical, incorporating bilingual teaching assistants and tutors could be a realistic step toward improving educational outcomes for all students.

Throughout our lives, we're taught about the existence of something greater than ourselves - a concept beyond our full comprehension. Whether through religious institutions like Sunday school or Temple, or through personal introspection, we seek understanding. While many embrace their inherited religious beliefs, others completely reject the notion of anything beyond their immediate understanding. Our spiritual journey often involves adopting, questioning, and sometimes changing our beliefs as we search for meaning and guidance in life.

The memory of my last months with my father remains vivid. One rainy evening, we shared a moment on our front porch, smoking cigarettes beneath the loud tin roof. When I asked about his favorite bird, he quietly answered, "A cardinal." I noticed his diminishing frame, his thinning hair, and that distant look in his eyes as he gazed into the rain. Words about his impending departure remained unspoken between us, too painful to acknowledge. Instead, I simply moved closer, sharing his silent contemplation of the June rainfall.

That December, just after I turned twenty-two, my father succumbed to cancer. The medical treatments had only prolonged his suffering beyond the doctors' expectations, leaving me questioning the purpose of it all. My faith crumbled; I couldn't reconcile a benevolent God with my father's suffering. In those dark nights, prayer felt futile, as if divine ears had long since turned away from my pleas.

I made the conscious choice not to witness his final moments, wanting to preserve memories of his life rather than his death. Understanding him as only a child could, I knew he wouldn't want me to watch his passing. Instead, I retreated to my bed for three days, waiting for news that never came through a phone call. The silence was deafening.

John Taylor of Caroline, though primarily a farmer, emerged as a passionate advocate for Republicanism, with his agricultural background deeply influencing his views on personal liberty and governance. His farming roots shaped his perspectives on sovereignty, constitutional matters, and judicial reform.

Taylor saw America's unique position as a new nation as advantageous, believing the absence of established traditions allowed for genuine self-governance. He championed the interconnected nature of natural rights, arguing that compromising one right would ultimately undermine all others, and thus these rights should remain beyond governmental control. He rejected the notion that society should mirror nature's law of the strongest, where physical strength and cunning prevailed.

In Taylor's vision of an ideal society, government needed to account for humanity's moral duality. He maintained that governmental virtues and vices reflected human nature itself. His definition of positive principles included protecting private property, advancing agriculture, and limiting capitalism. Taylor believed that while self-interest drove human behavior, it only became problematic when it led to the formation of groups that exploited others rather than contributing to the common good.

As a Republican, Taylor advocated for a strict but contextual interpretation of the Constitution, favoring a minimal federal government limited to explicitly granted powers. He warned against an expansive federal system, seeing it as potentially tyrannical due to its cost. Notably, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the nation's true founding document, as it emphasized state sovereignty over national unity. However, he cautioned against purely literal constitutional interpretation, stressing the importance of understanding the founders' original intent.

I gazed downward, observing the scene before me with detached precision. My mind processed what I saw without emotional involvement, analyzing the view with mechanical efficiency. Thoughts flowed through my consciousness like water, barely registering before disappearing.

Years ago, following a colleague's suggestion, I had invested in "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since childhood, I'd aspired to learn drawing, and this book covered everything from basic tools to cognitive processes. One key technique involved using a frame to isolate portions of complex scenes, making them more manageable to reproduce – like simplifying a kitchen scene to focus solely on a fruit bowl.

But now, facing what lay before me, I couldn't apply such artistic principles. I was too stunned, too captivated by the sight. While great artists had their signature periods and color palettes – Picasso's blues, Monet's greens, Renaissance masters' vibrant spectrums – here was the beginning of my own masterpiece: a study in brown.

My fingers grasped my tool, muscles engaging as I moved with what could have been artistic grace. The water moved smoothly, crystal-clear at first, with particles breaking free and disappearing into the current. Growing increasingly frustrated, I hit the toilet handle again, but the stubborn brown mass remained fixed to the bowl's bottom, unmoved.

There I stood in my Rite Aid uniform, green tie choking my neck, mop in hand, contemplating this unwanted "gift" left by some inconsiderate customer. After several unsuccessful flushes and moments of philosophical resignation, I reached for the toilet paper, wrapping my hand extensively until it resembled protective wear. Standing straight before bending forward, I lowered my hand toward the bowl, reminiscent of retrieving a holiday roast from the oven...

Young drivers face significant risks on the road, with multiple factors contributing to this dangerous situation. Research from the National Institutes of Health indicates that adolescents' brain development hasn't reached the level necessary for safe driving, while their lack of experience further compounds the problem. This inexperience leads to higher rates of fatal crashes, vehicle rollovers, excessive speed incidents, and road departures.

The danger intensifies when teenagers drive with other young passengers, a common occurrence. Research by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center demonstrates a clear link between passenger age and accident frequency. While some states, including California, have implemented provisional licensing systems restricting driving hours and young passengers, these measures may not be sufficient.

The fundamental issue remains that young drivers, as a demographic, struggle to manage driving risks and responsibilities effectively. Dr. Marvin Zuckerman's research, as reported in USA Today, indicates that individuals under 19-20 years old have a natural inclination toward thrill-seeking behavior. This suggests that delaying driving privileges until this tendency diminishes could be beneficial. The situation becomes more pressing considering the upcoming surge of potential young drivers from Baby-Boomer families.

A potential solution could involve nationwide legislation establishing 18 as the minimum driving age. This approach would maintain driver's education in schools while implementing a graduated licensing system with provisional permits and mandatory training hours, similar to existing state requirements like California's current model of 6 hours of professional instruction and 50 hours of supervised practice. Given that teen driving statistics show similar patterns across all states, a uniform national policy could effectively address this safety concern.

This proposed legislative approach, while not revolutionary, could help protect young lives on America's roads.

This article examines three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Beginning with a definition, followed by diagnostic procedures and indicators, it concludes with strategies for educators supporting CAPD students in mainstream classrooms.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), involves the brain's inability to effectively process auditory information, despite normal hearing function. The condition affects how the central nervous system interprets sound, rather than the ability to hear sounds themselves. Individuals with CAPD can detect sounds normally but struggle with processing and distinguishing between different sounds, such as separating speech from background noise.

The disorder's history dates back to the 1950s, when it was initially termed "auditory imperception." Significant developments occurred when Italian researchers began developing diagnostic tests in 1954, followed by Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing in 1961. A pivotal 1977 national conference sparked increased research interest in pediatric CAPD.

CAPD symptoms include difficulties with sound localization, distinguishing between different sounds, recognizing sound patterns, detecting vocal nuances (such as sarcasm), processing sequential sounds, and synthesizing auditory information meaningfully. These challenges can significantly impact daily functioning and communication.

Diagnosis involves comprehensive screening through various methods, including behavioral observations and auditory function tests, typically conducted by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. The diagnostic process may incorporate questionnaires, behavioral observations, and various auditory response tests. Currently, there is no single standardized diagnostic tool, and the disorder's exact cause remains unknown. Advanced diagnostic procedures may include acoustic signal testing and response measurements within the ear.

My goal in pursuing social work education is to build a career with the Division of Family and Children Services, focusing on supporting troubled families and protecting abused or neglected children. I bring essential values to the field, including dedication to service, respectful conduct, ethical behavior, and a commitment to both fostering better interpersonal relationships and maintaining professional growth. These principles aren't merely professional requirements – they reflect my personal beliefs.

My journey to social work wasn't immediate. During my academic years, I observed many peers struggling with personal issues, often through unhealthy coping mechanisms. This led me to pursue Psychology at Piedmont College, graduating in 2009. A pivotal moment came that summer when I met a teenage boy seeking refuge from abusive parents at a friend's house. After he reported his parents to authorities, I visited their home to offer assistance. Drawing on my psychology background, I spoke with the police and later the parents, who dismissed serious family conflicts as "simple disputes." This experience crystallized my decision to pursue social work, specifically to advocate for children in troubled family situations.

Social justice is another cornerstone of my professional and personal philosophy. I've always questioned society's paradoxical approach to individuality – claiming to value it while simultaneously promoting conformity. Throughout my academic career, I've actively challenged social injustice through various forms of personal expression and activism, including involvement with GSBA and opposing discrimination and racism. My commitment to fighting social injustice remains unwavering and will continue to inform my professional practice.

This paper examines insomnia through the lens of both Biological and Sociocultural models. While the biological perspective examines inherited genetic factors and medical conditions, the sociocultural approach considers environmental influences, including racial, ethnic, demographic, and socioeconomic factors. The paper analyzes relevant research studies through these models and evaluates their respective strengths and limitations.

Sleep disorders can be classified into three main categories: primary sleep disorders, those connected to other mental disorders, and those linked to various other causes. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, while mental disorder-related sleep issues are connected to Axis I or II disorders. Additional sleep disorders may stem from medical conditions or substance use. Dyssomnias encompass several conditions, including Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia NOS. Primary Insomnia involves difficulty maintaining sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia causes excessive sleepiness, both lasting at least one month. Narcolepsy is characterized by cataplexy and/or automatic REM. Parasomnias, which involve abnormal behaviors or physiological events during sleep, include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias NOS.

The biological model emphasizes the role of genetics and physiology in sleep disorders. Research involving hypothalamic neurons containing orexin demonstrates their crucial role in sleep-wake regulation. Studies with mice revealed that GABAB receptors on orexin neurons influence sleep states, with GABAA receptor activation promoting sleep. The research suggests potential applications to human sleep patterns and implies both genetic and environmental influences on sleep regulation. Any receptor dysfunction could necessitate medical intervention for proper sleep. From a sociocultural perspective, inherited sleep regulation problems could significantly impact an individual's educational, professional, and daily activities, particularly those requiring sustained attention and focus.

As a student who has spent over two years at University Park, I've experienced firsthand the challenges of campus mobility. During my freshman year in East Halls, particularly Stuart Hall, I faced lengthy walks to central campus locations like Willard building, sometimes taking 25 minutes, especially in State College's often unfavorable weather. The campus has undergone significant expansion, as evidenced by an alumnus's account of how East Halls was once isolated by vacant land that has since been developed with athletic fields, new facilities like the Creamery and health services building, and residential complexes. This growth has intensified transportation challenges across campus.

The bicycle emerges as the ideal solution for campus mobility, though its effectiveness depends on both student adoption and appropriate infrastructure. This perspective was reinforced by a friend who recently returned to cycling, acknowledging its practical superiority over other transportation methods. Cycling not only promotes physical health but also offers remarkable efficiency – a simple breakfast can fuel a 30-mile journey.

Now living off-campus at a distance comparable to some dorms, I've found that purchasing a bicycle was an excellent investment. It transforms what would be a 25-minute walk to Thomas building into a mere 5-minute ride. While Pollock Road offers the most direct route, it presents its own challenges for cyclists. Though walking remains an option, it's impractical for my schedule. Without a bike, I would spend an additional 2.5 hours weekly just walking to and from Thomas building alone, not counting other campus destinations – time I simply cannot afford to lose.

In Brave New World, Aldous Huxley presents a critique of advancing technology and capitalism through a dystopian society where collective identity supersedes individuality, and instant gratification is the primary goal. The World Controller manipulates the population, who are essentially trapped within a prescribed ideology. Through a Marxist interpretation, the novel reveals Huxley's skepticism toward these developing systems, employing concepts like homogeneity and reification to comment on contemporary economic developments.

The novel illustrates Marxist false consciousness, where citizens are deliberately kept ignorant of true class relationships, focusing instead on personal pleasure. This is achieved through systematic conditioning, particularly evident in how lower castes (Delta, Gamma, etc.) are programmed to consume and pursue pleasure mindlessly. The World Controller's hegemonic control ensures complete dominance over these social classes, who unconsciously embrace capitalistic and consumerist ideologies. While upper classes (Alphas and Betas) have the capacity to recognize this manipulation, most, except for a few like Bernard, accept their prescribed roles without question.

The absence of genuine interpersonal connections in the novel is notable, with characters lacking psychological depth. This suggests Huxley's view that the combination of technology and capitalism strips humanity of authenticity and free will. Relationships remain superficial, with men objectifying women's physical attributes and women casually discussing their encounters. The various social classes' acceptance of their positions reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact, while their unwavering conformity exemplifies the Marxist concept of the proletariat being placated through consumerism and false promises of superiority, provided they maintain their designated social role.

Reflecting on a course about Islam I took at CBC nearly four years ago, I recall intense debates about Islam's nature as potentially hostile. This question seems even more pertinent today. Since 9/11, I've noticed media coverage shift dramatically from initial hostility toward Islam to extreme acceptance in American society, exemplified by the emergence of Barack Obama as a presidential candidate despite his family's Muslim connections.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography presents an interesting contradiction to my previous understanding of his character. While I had learned that Muhammad primarily spread Islam through conquest and forced conversion, the biography portrays him as a misunderstood, humble figure whose followers voluntarily embraced his teachings after witnessing his truth.

I noticed striking parallels between Jesus's ministry and Muhammad's reported miracles, such as the multiplication of mutton and milk to feed forty men. This portrayal seems designed to present Muhammad as a modest prophet whose truth was self-evident through miracles. However, this approach appears to diminish Jesus Christ's unique miracles and ministry by creating similar narratives for Muhammad.

The biography frequently relies on chain-of-narration stories to validate conversions to Islam, where accounts are passed through multiple intermediaries. Rather than strengthening the credibility of these accounts, this method of storytelling actually makes them seem less reliable.

Most concerning is the biography's portrayal of Muhammad as a humble, wise, and gentle religious leader, which appears to conflict with historical accounts of his rise to power. This raises questions about whether contemporary Muslims are fully aware of the historical context of Muhammad's ascension to leadership.

Christianity rapidly diverged from Jesus's original teachings after his death, with subsequent developments taking the faith increasingly further from its roots. Today, despite traditional resistance, there appears to be a growing progressive consciousness that may herald a significant transformation in Christian thought. In the coming years, Christians are likely to develop a stronger interest in distinguishing between original teachings and later doctrinal additions. This will eventually trigger a massive reversal in Christian historical development, with believers gradually stripping away accumulated doctrinal layers to rediscover Jesus's fundamental message.

This movement, expected to sweep through Western nations, will likely maintain the church's institutional strength while paradoxically reducing the current theological diversity within Christianity. Instead of the present denominational fragmentation, we'll witness increasing uniformity in belief and practice across different Christian groups. Such major historical reversals aren't unprecedented – consider how the Roman Empire shifted from persecuting Christians to embracing Christianity, or how America evolved from slavery to having African-American leadership.

This religious transformation will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus's teachings metaphorically rather than literally. To understand this evolution, we must look back to Christianity's origins in Judaism. Before the Roman occupation of Jerusalem in 63 BCE, Judaism had already established its core principles of monotheism, divine revelation, and scriptural authority. The Jewish community was diverse, split between Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the general population.

Through the lens of The Jungle, we can observe humanity's inherent selfishness and greed. The novel illustrates how people primarily focus on their own advancement while disregarding those beneath them in social status. This theme is particularly evident in the portrayal of factory owners and managers, who ruthlessly pursue expansion and profit without consideration for collateral damage.

Sinclair vividly depicts this through imagery of industrial pollution, with "chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," symbolizing the owners' complete disregard for environmental and human welfare. They show no concern for the pollution their factories produce or the unsanitary conditions in Packingtown's animal pens.

The exploitation extends deeply into labor practices. The workplace is described as a "seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds" where profit consistently trumps human dignity. Workers face arbitrary layoffs, dangerous working conditions, and exhausting schedules, with no job security or protective regulations. The absence of labor laws during this period allowed management to operate without accountability, forcing workers to endure hazardous conditions both in factories and their living environments.

The situation in Packingtown effectively created a modern form of slavery, particularly affecting poor and immigrant populations. Workers were trapped in a system that offered no support, protection, or escape routes. Even labor unions, which should have protected workers, often exploited them instead. The parallel between these industrial workers and chattel slavery is stark, as both systems operated through brutal exploitation by unscrupulous overseers, creating environments where suffering and moral degradation were inevitable consequences of the system.

Edgar Allan Poe considered "Dream-land" among his finest poetic works. The poem features the word "Thulé" twice, which has historical roots in Virgil's writings about a mythical northern island beyond Britain that marked the boundary of the ancient Greek world. While Virgil's influence is undeniable, there's a more contemporary source worth noting, given Poe's known interest in German literature.

This connection is particularly significant as it demonstrates Poe's knowledge of Goethe's work. Scholar Karl J. Arndt, in his analysis "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," suggests that Poe was emulating Goethe's style.

Goethe, as noted in the Oxford Companion to English Literature, was renowned for his poetic drama "Faust," published in two installments (1808 and 1832).
